                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d353">
                <head>No. 349.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Edward Thornton</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Evarts</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-01-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 12, 1881</date>. (Received January
                        12.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note of the 10th instant, inclosing copy of a letter addressed by the
                    Treasury <pb facs="0700" n="576" xml:id="pg_576"/> Department to the collector
                    of customs at Suspension Bridge, concerning the transportation of merchandise in
                    bond, from one port to another in Canada, by way of Suspension Bridge and
                    Ogdensburg, N. Y., and to inform you that I am this day forwarding a copy of it
                    to the governor general of Canada, for communication to the customs department
                    of the Dominion.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>EDW’D THORNTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
